ion\nerrors and precluded from local model aggregations. The\nconvergence upper bound of D-FL is rigorously analyzed.\nInsights are drawn to help optimally decide the number of\nlocal aggregations per local training round, adapting to the\ntopology and channel conditions of D-FL.\nThe key contributions of the paper are as follows.\n•We consider a new scenario of D-FL under imperfect\nchannels, where the initialization of local training is\ndesigned to allow different devices’ models to converge\nafter training.\n•We derive the bias of locally aggregated D-FL models\nunder imperfect channels from the ideal global model,arXiv:2405.12894v1  [cs.DC]  21 May 20242\nand analyze the convergence upper bound of D-FL under\nimperfect channels based on the bias.\n•We reveal that increasing local iterations facilitates con-\nvergence in imperfect channels, while increasing local\naggregations entails a trade-off with the accumulation of\ncommunication errors within the convergence bound.\n•We minimize the convergence upper bound by optimizing\nthe number of local aggregations to restrain the impact\nof communication errors when the channel conditions\nare unknown a-priori . On the other hand, the a-priori\nknowledge of the channels can help mitigate the impact\nso that more local aggregations improve convergence.\nExtensiveexperiments to validate\nthe new convergence analysis and algorithm of D-FL. Follow-\ning a random geometric graph model [30], a 12-vertex graph\nwith an undirected and connected topology is generated at\nrandom. Table I lists the coordinates of the 12 vertices. When\nthere are N≤12participating devices, we select the first N\nvertices. The connectivity density of edges (i.e., transmitter-\nreceiver pairs) in the topological graph of the network is ρ;\nin other words, the number of transmitter-receiver pairs in the\nconsidered network is ρ×N(N−1)\n2. By\n\n            **Your Task**\n\n            Use only the Introduction above as your literature context. External paper databases, arXiv, author-profile APIs, and web search are not part of this benchmark.\n\n            1. **Context analysis**: Summarize the problem setting, prior approaches mentioned in the Introduction, and implied gaps you can infer from that text alone.\n\n            2. **Brainstorming**: Collaboratively brainstorm potential research ideas that build upon or address gaps in the Introduction.\n\n            3. **Summarization**: Summarize your collective ideas.\n\n            4. **Formulate a New Research Idea**: Develop a new research proposal in the format of the '5q', defined below:\n\n               **Here is a high-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning.**\n\n               **Here are the five core questions:**\n\n               **[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\n\n               Formulate the specific research question you aim to address. Only output one question and do not include any more information.\n\n               **[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\n\n               Explain the broader implications of solving this problem for the research community.\n               Discuss how such a paper will affect future research.\n               Discuss how addressing this question could advance knowledge or lead to practical applications.\n\n               **[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\n\n               Discuss the challenges and complexities involved in solving this problem.\n               Explain why naive or straightforward approaches may fail.\n               Identify any technical, theoretical, or practical obstacles that need to be overcome. MAKE IT CLEAR.\n\n               **[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\n\n               Identify gaps or limitations in previous research or existing solutions.\n               Discuss any barriers that have prevented this problem from being solved until now.\n               Explain how your approach differs from or improves upon prior work. MAKE IT CLEAR.\n\n               **[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\n\n               Outline your proposed methodology in detail, including the method, dataset, and metrics that you plan to use.\n               Describe the expected outcomes. MAKE IT CLEAR.\n\n            Please work together to produce the '5q' for your proposed research idea.\n\n            Good luck!\n            "}, 'task_results': [{'agent_id': 'agent1', 'result': "Result from the model:### Context Analysis\n\n**Problem Setting:**\nThe paper focuses on decentralized federated learning (D-FL) under imperfect communication channels. It analyzes the impact of imperfect channels on D-FL and determines the optimal number of local aggregations per training round to balance convergence and communication errors. The study derives the bias of locally aggregated models under imperfect channels and analyzes the convergence upper bound of D-FL based on this bias.\n\n**Prior Approaches:**\n- Previous studies have considered D-FL protocols under imperfect channels.\n- However, none have analyzed the impact of the accumulation of communication errors resulting from multiple local aggregations.\n\n**Implied Gaps:**\n- The accumulation of communication errors due to multiple local aggregations is not well-understood.\n- There is a need for a method to optimally decide the number of local aggregations per training round, adapting to network topology and channel conditions.\n- The impact of mobility and non-i.i.d. errors in communication links on the convergence and reliability of D-FL is not addressed.\n- Model selection for D-FL under fast-changing fading channels is an unexplored area.\n\n### Brainstorming\n\n1. **Model Selection for D-FL:**\n   - Develop adaptive algorithms that allow devices to select the most suitable models for aggregation based on current channel conditions and model performance.\n\n2. **Impact of Mobility:**\n   - Investigate how mobility affects the convergence and reliability of D-FL, especially in scenarios where devices frequently change their positions and communication links.\n\n3. **Non-i.i.d. Errors:**\n   - Study the impact of non-i.i.d. errors in communication links on the convergence of D-FL and propose robust algorithms to mitigate these effects.\n\n4. **Enhanced Convergence Analysis:**\n   - Extend the current convergence analysis to include more complex network topologies and varying channel conditions, providing a more comprehensive understanding of D-FL behavior.\n\n5. **Privacy-Preserving Mechanisms:**\n   - Integrate privacy-preserving techniques into D-FL to ensure that sensitive data remains secure while optimizing resource allocation and communication.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe key gaps identified in the Introduction revolve around the accumulation of communication errors due to multiple local aggregations, the impact of mobility and non-i.i.d. errors, and the need for adaptive model selection in D-FL. Potential research ideas include developing adaptive algorithms for model selection, investigating the impact of mobility, studying non-i.i.d. errors, enhancing convergence analysis, and integrating privacy-preserving mechanisms.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field:**\nDecentralized Federated Learning (D-FL) is a promising approach for training machine learning models across distributed devices while preserving data privacy. However, the performance of D-FL is significantly impacted by imperfect communication channels, which can lead to communication errors and degraded convergence.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nHow can we adaptively select the most suitable models for aggregation in D-FL under fast-changing fading channels to optimize convergence and minimize communication errors?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nAddressing this problem is crucial for enhancing the reliability and efficiency of D-FL in dynamic environments. By developing adaptive model selection algorithms, we can improve the performance of D-FL, making it more robust to varying channel conditions and better suited for real-world applications. This research will contribute to the development of more resilient and efficient decentralized learning systems.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nThe challenge lies in designing algorithms that can dynamically assess and select the best models for aggregation based on current channel conditions and model performance. This requires a deep understanding of both communication theory and machine learning, as well as the ability to handle the uncertainties and complexities inherent in dynamic network environments. Naive approaches may fail to account for the interdependencies between channel conditions and model performance, leading to suboptimal convergence and increased communication errors.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has focused on analyzing the impact of imperfect channels on D-FL but has not addressed the specific problem of adaptive model selection under fast-changing fading channels. The complexity of designing algorithms that can dynamically assess and select the best models for aggregation in real-time is a significant barrier. Additionally, the need to balance convergence and communication errors while adapting to varying channel conditions adds to the challenge.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology involves developing adaptive algorithms that leverage machine learning techniques to dynamically assess and select the best models for aggregation based on current channel conditions and model performance. The approach will be validated through extensive numerical simulations using real-world datasets and network topologies. The expected outcomes include improved convergence rates, reduced communication errors, and enhanced reliability of D-FL in dynamic environments.\n"}, {'agent_id': 'agent2', 'result': "Result from the model:### Context Analysis\n\n**Problem Setting:**\nThe paper focuses on decentralized federated learning (D-FL) under imperfect communication channels. It aims to determine the optimal number of local aggregations per training round to balance convergence and communication errors. The study derives the bias of locally aggregated models under imperfect channels and analyzes the convergence upper bound of D-FL based on this bias.\n\n**Prior Approaches:**\n- Previous studies have considered D-FL protocols under imperfect channels.\n- However, none have analyzed the impact of the accumulation of communication errors resulting from multiple local aggregations.\n\n**Implied Gaps:**\n- The accumulation of communication errors due to multiple local aggregations is not well understood.\n- There is a need for a method to optimally decide the number of local aggregations per training round, adapting to network topology and channel conditions.\n- The impact of mobility and non-i.i.d. errors in communication links on the convergence and reliability of D-FL is not addressed.\n- Model selection for D-FL under fast-changing fading channels is an unexplored area.\n\n### Brainstorming\n\n1. **Impact of Mobility and Non-i.i.d. Errors:**\n   - Investigate how mobility and non-i.i.d. errors in communication links affect the convergence and reliability of D-FL.\n   - Develop adaptive strategies to mitigate these effects.\n\n2. **Model Selection for D-FL:**\n   - Study model selection techniques for D-FL where each device can adaptively select models for aggregation under fast-changing fading channels.\n   - Explore the use of machine learning techniques to predict and select the best models for aggregation.\n\n3. **Robustness to Communication Errors:**\n   - Develop robust algorithms that can handle communication errors more effectively.\n   - Investigate the use of error correction codes and redundancy to improve the reliability of D-FL.\n\n4. **Network Topology and Channel Conditions:**\n   - Develop methods to dynamically adjust the number of local aggregations based on the network topology and channel conditions.\n   - Use graph theory and network analysis to optimize the aggregation process.\n\n5. **Simulation and Validation:**\n   - Conduct extensive simulations to validate the new convergence analysis and algorithms.\n   - Use real-world datasets and network topologies to test the proposed methods.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe key gaps identified in the Introduction revolve around the accumulation of communication errors due to multiple local aggregations, the impact of mobility and non-i.i.d. errors, and the need for adaptive model selection techniques in D-FL. Potential research ideas include developing robust algorithms, adaptive strategies, and methods to dynamically adjust the number of local aggregations based on network conditions.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nDecentralized Federated Learning (D-FL) is a promising approach for training machine learning models across distributed devices while preserving privacy. However, the performance of D-FL is significantly impacted by imperfect communication channels, which can lead to communication errors and degraded convergence.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nHow can we dynamically adjust the number of local aggregations in D-FL to balance convergence and communication errors under imperfect channels?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nAddressing this problem is crucial for improving the reliability and efficiency of D-FL in real-world scenarios where communication channels are often imperfect. Solving this problem will lead to more robust and practical D-FL systems, enhancing their applicability in various domains such as mobile edge computing and IoT.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nThe challenge lies in developing algorithms that can dynamically adjust the number of local aggregations based on the network topology and channel conditions. Naive approaches may fail due to the complex interplay between communication errors and model convergence. Overcoming this requires a deep understanding of both communication theory and optimization techniques.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has not fully addressed the impact of multiple local aggregations on communication errors. Existing solutions often assume perfect channels or do not consider the dynamic nature of network conditions. Our approach will differ by incorporating real-time network analysis and adaptive strategies to optimize local aggregations.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nOur approach will involve developing a dynamic adjustment algorithm that uses network topology and channel condition data to optimize the number of local aggregations. We will conduct extensive simulations using real-world datasets and network topologies to validate our algorithm. The expected outcomes include improved convergence rates and reduced communication errors in D-FL systems.\n"}, {'agent_id': 'agent3', 'result': "Result from the model:### Context Analysis\n\n**Problem Setting:**\nThe paper focuses on decentralized federated learning (D-FL) under imperfect communication channels. It examines the impact of local aggregations on the convergence of D-FL models, revealing that excessive local aggregations can accumulate communication errors and degrade convergence. The study derives the bias of locally aggregated models compared to ideal global models and analyzes the convergence upper bound of D-FL under imperfect channels.\n\n**Prior Approaches:**\n- Previous studies have considered D-FL protocols under imperfect channels.\n- However, none have analyzed the impact of the accumulation of communication errors resulting from multiple local aggregations.\n\n**Implied Gaps:**\n- The need to determine the optimal number of local aggregations per training round to balance convergence and communication errors.\n- The impact of communication errors on the convergence of D-FL models.\n- The role of network topology and channel conditions in optimizing local aggregations.\n\n### Brainstorming\n\n1. **Optimal Local Aggregation Strategies:**\n   - Develop adaptive algorithms that dynamically adjust the number of local aggregations based on real-time channel conditions and network topology.\n\n2. **Error Mitigation Techniques:**\n   - Investigate error correction codes and robust communication protocols to minimize the impact of communication errors on local aggregations.\n\n3. **Model Consistency and Synchronization:**\n   - Explore methods to maintain model consistency across devices in the presence of communication errors, ensuring that local models do not diverge significantly from the global model.\n\n4. **Impact of Mobility and Non-i.i.d. Errors:**\n   - Study the effects of mobility and non-i.i.d. errors in communication links on the convergence and reliability of D-FL.\n\n5. **Model Selection for D-FL:**\n   - Develop adaptive model selection strategies that allow devices to choose the most suitable models for aggregation under fast-changing fading channels.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe key gaps identified in the Introduction revolve around optimizing local aggregations in D-FL under imperfect communication channels. Potential research ideas include developing adaptive algorithms, error mitigation techniques, and model consistency methods to enhance the convergence and reliability of D-FL models.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight:**\nThe impact of imperfect communication channels on decentralized federated learning (D-FL) is significant, affecting the convergence of models and the accuracy of training. Optimizing local aggregations is crucial for balancing convergence and communication errors, but existing research has not fully addressed this challenge.\n\n**Five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nWhat is the optimal number of local aggregations per training round in decentralized federated learning under imperfect communication channels, and how can it be dynamically adjusted based on real-time channel conditions and network topology?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nSolving this problem is crucial for enhancing the convergence and reliability of D-FL models in real-world scenarios where communication channels are often imperfect. It will lead to more efficient and robust federated learning systems, benefiting both service providers and end-users by improving model accuracy and reducing training time.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nDetermining the optimal number of local aggregations is challenging due to the dynamic nature of communication channels and network topologies. Naive approaches that do not account for real-time conditions may lead to suboptimal convergence and increased communication errors. Overcoming these challenges requires developing adaptive algorithms that can efficiently balance convergence and error accumulation.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has not fully addressed the impact of multiple local aggregations on communication errors and convergence. Existing solutions often assume perfect channels or do not dynamically adjust local aggregations based on real-time conditions. This research aims to fill these gaps by developing adaptive algorithms that can optimize local aggregations in the presence of imperfect communication channels.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology involves developing adaptive algorithms that dynamically adjust the number of local aggregations based on real-time channel conditions and network topology. The approach will leverage techniques from distributed optimization and communication theory to minimize the impact of communication errors on local aggregations. Experiments will be conducted using a random geometric graph model to simulate different network topologies and channel conditions. The expected outcomes include improved convergence rates and reduced communication errors, demonstrating the effectiveness of the proposed approach in enhancing the reliability and efficiency of D-FL models.\n"}, {'agent_id': 'agent4', 'result': "Result from the model:### Context Analysis\n\n**Problem Setting:**\nThe paper focuses on decentralized federated learning (D-FL) under imperfect communication channels. It examines the impact of local aggregations on the convergence of D-FL models, considering the bias introduced by imperfect channels and the trade-off between local aggregations and communication errors.\n\n**Prior Approaches:**\n- Previous studies have considered D-FL protocols under imperfect channels.\n- However, none have analyzed the impact of the accumulation of communication errors resulting from multiple local aggregations.\n\n**Implied Gaps:**\n- The need to determine the optimal number of local aggregations per training round to balance convergence and communication errors.\n- The impact of network topology and channel conditions on the optimal number of local aggregations.\n- The need for a rigorous analysis of the convergence upper bound of D-FL under imperfect channels.\n\n### Brainstorming\n\n1. **Optimal Aggregation Strategy:**\n   - Develop a dynamic aggregation strategy that adapts to changing channel conditions and network topology.\n   - Use reinforcement learning to optimize the number of local aggregations in real-time.\n\n2. **Channel Modeling:**\n   - Incorporate realistic channel models to better understand the impact of communication errors on D-FL.\n   - Develop robust algorithms that can handle varying channel conditions without prior knowledge.\n\n3. **Model Consistency:**\n   - Investigate methods to maintain model consistency across devices in the presence of communication errors.\n   - Explore error correction techniques to mitigate the impact of corrupted local models.\n\n4. **Scalability:**\n   - Ensure that the proposed algorithms are scalable to large-scale D-FL systems.\n   - Analyze the computational complexity and communication overhead of the proposed methods.\n\n5. **Adaptive Model Selection:**\n   - Develop adaptive model selection strategies that allow devices to choose the best models for aggregation under fast-changing fading channels.\n   - Investigate the impact of model selection on convergence and reliability.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe key gaps identified in the Introduction revolve around determining the optimal number of local aggregations in D-FL under imperfect channels, understanding the impact of network topology and channel conditions, and developing robust algorithms that can handle varying channel conditions without prior knowledge. Potential research ideas include dynamic aggregation strategies, channel modeling, model consistency, scalability, and adaptive model selection.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of the research field:**\nDecentralized Federated Learning (D-FL) is a promising approach for distributed machine learning, but its performance is significantly impacted by imperfect communication channels. The optimal number of local aggregations per training round is crucial for balancing convergence and communication errors, yet this aspect has not been thoroughly investigated.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nWhat is the optimal number of local aggregations per training round in D-FL under imperfect communication channels, and how does it adapt to network topology and channel conditions?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nDetermining the optimal number of local aggregations is critical for improving the convergence and reliability of D-FL systems in real-world scenarios. This research will provide a deeper understanding of the trade-offs between local aggregations and communication errors, leading to more efficient and robust D-FL algorithms. The findings will have significant implications for the development of scalable and reliable decentralized learning systems.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nThe problem is challenging due to the dynamic nature of communication channels and network topologies. Naive approaches that assume perfect channels or fixed aggregation strategies may fail to account for the complexities of real-world communication environments. Overcoming this requires developing sophisticated algorithms that can adapt to varying conditions and minimize the impact of communication errors.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has focused on the impact of imperfect channels on D-FL but has not thoroughly investigated the optimal number of local aggregations. The complexity of adapting to dynamic channel conditions and network topologies has been a significant barrier. This research aims to fill this gap by developing adaptive algorithms that can handle varying conditions without prior knowledge.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed approach involves developing a dynamic aggregation strategy using reinforcement learning to optimize the number of local aggregations in real-time. The algorithm will adapt to changing channel conditions and network topologies. The methodology will be validated through extensive experiments on CNN and ResNet-18 models using a random geometric graph model to simulate network topologies. The expected outcomes include a significant improvement in training accuracy and convergence rates compared to existing methods, especially in scenarios with unknown channel conditions.\n"}, {'agent_id': 'agent5', 'result': "Result from the model:### Context Analysis\n\n**Problem Setting:**\nThe paper focuses on decentralized federated learning (D-FL) under imperfect communication channels. It examines the impact of local aggregations on the convergence of D-FL models, revealing that excessive local aggregations can accumulate communication errors and degrade convergence. The study aims to determine the optimal number of local aggregations per training round to balance the trade-off between convergence and communication error accumulation.\n\n**Prior Approaches:**\nPrevious studies have considered D-FL protocols under imperfect channels but have not analyzed the impact of the accumulation of communication errors resulting from multiple local aggregations. The current paper addresses this gap by deriving the bias of locally aggregated D-FL models under imperfect channels and analyzing the convergence upper bound based on this bias.\n\n**Implied Gaps:**\n- The impact of mobility and non-i.i.d. errors in communication links on the convergence and reliability of D-FL.\n- Model selection for D-FL, where each device can adaptively select models for aggregation under fast-changing fading channels.\n- The effect of a-priori knowledge of channel conditions on the optimal number of local aggregations.\n\n### Brainstorming\n\n1. **Impact of Mobility and Non-i.i.d. Errors:**\n   - Investigate how mobility and non-i.i.d. errors in communication links affect the convergence and reliability of D-FL.\n   - Develop adaptive algorithms that can handle these dynamic conditions.\n\n2. **Model Selection for D-FL:**\n   - Explore methods for adaptive model selection in D-FL, where devices can choose the best models for aggregation based on current channel conditions.\n   - Develop criteria for model selection that optimize performance under varying channel conditions.\n\n3. **A-priori Knowledge of Channel Conditions:**\n   - Study how a-priori knowledge of channel conditions can be leveraged to optimize the number of local aggregations.\n   - Develop algorithms that utilize this knowledge to improve convergence and reduce communication errors.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe research aims to extend the current understanding of D-FL under imperfect channels by addressing the impact of mobility and non-i.i.d. errors, developing adaptive model selection methods, and leveraging a-priori knowledge of channel conditions to optimize the number of local aggregations.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of the research field:**\nDecentralized Federated Learning (D-FL) is a promising approach for distributed machine learning, but its performance is significantly impacted by imperfect communication channels. The optimal number of local aggregations per training round is crucial for balancing convergence and communication error accumulation.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nHow can we adaptively select models for aggregation in D-FL under fast-changing fading channels to optimize performance?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nAddressing this problem is crucial for enhancing the reliability and efficiency of D-FL in dynamic environments. It will enable D-FL to better handle real-world communication challenges, leading to improved convergence and accuracy. This research will advance the field by providing practical solutions for adaptive model selection in D-FL.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nThe challenge lies in developing algorithms that can dynamically adapt to changing channel conditions while maintaining optimal performance. Naive approaches may fail due to the complexity of modeling and predicting channel variations. Technical obstacles include the need for efficient communication protocols and robust model selection criteria.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has focused on static channel conditions and has not addressed the dynamic nature of real-world communication environments. The complexity of modeling fast-changing fading channels and developing adaptive algorithms has been a significant barrier. This research aims to fill this gap by introducing novel methods for adaptive model selection.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology involves developing adaptive model selection algorithms that leverage a-priori knowledge of channel conditions and real-time channel feedback. The approach will be validated using simulations and experiments on CNN and ResNet-18 models. Key metrics include training accuracy, convergence speed, and robustness to channel variations. Expected outcomes include improved performance of D-FL in dynamic environments and a deeper understanding of the impact of channel conditions on model aggregation strategies.\n"}], 'summary': '```json\n{\n  "[Question 1] - What is the problem?": "How can the optimal number of local aggregations per training round be determined in decentralized federated learning (D-FL) under imperfect communication channels to balance convergence and communication error accumulation?",\n\n  "[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?": "Solving this problem is crucial for improving the reliability and efficiency of D-FL in real-world scenarios where communication channels are often imperfect. It will advance the theoretical understanding of D-FL under challenging network conditions and lead to more robust and practical D-FL systems. This research will influence future studies on D-FL, particularly in adapting to dynamic and unreliable communication environments, and could have significant implications for applications in mobile and edge computing.",\n\n  "[Question 3] - Why is it hard?": "Determining the optimal number of local aggregations involves balancing convergence speed with the accumulation of communication errors, which is complex due to the dynamic nature of communication channels and network topologies. Naive approaches may fail because they do not account for the cumulative impact of communication errors over multiple local aggregations. Technical challenges include modeling the impact of communication errors accurately and developing algorithms that can adapt to varying channel conditions in real-time. Theoretical challenges involve deriving precise convergence bounds and understanding the interplay between local aggregations and communication errors.",\n\n  "[Question 4] - Why hasn\'t it been solved before?": "Previous research on D-FL under imperfect channels has not focused on the specific issue of communication error accumulation from multiple local aggregations. Existing solutions often assume perfect or static communication conditions, which are not representative of real-world scenarios. The gap in understanding the impact of communication errors on convergence has prevented the development of optimal strategies for local aggregations. This research addresses this gap by providing a rigorous analysis of the convergence upper bound and deriving the bias of locally aggregated models under imperfect channels.",\n\n  "[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?": "The proposed approach involves deriving a mathematical model to quantify the bias introduced by communication errors in locally aggregated D-FL models. We will analyze the convergence upper bound of D-FL based on this bias and develop an algorithm to optimize the number of local aggregations per training round. The methodology will include simulations using a random geometric graph model to represent network topologies and experiments with CNN and ResNet-18 models to validate the convergence analysis. Key metrics will include training accuracy, convergence speed, and communication error rates. T